title.narrative: Output 1.3. By 2020, multi-sectoral coordination and technical and functional capacity of partners strengthened to scale up and sustain high-impact child nutrition interventions, with a focus on the first 1,000 days of life, to reduce stunting and other forms of malnutrition.

description.narrative: UNICEF support to the Regulatory Impact Assessment of the draft National Nutrition Policy and to the integration of the District Nutrition Action Plans in the District Development Plans in 18 focus districts contributed to further strengthening of enabling environment for nutrition. At service delivery level, as a result of UNICEF support 460,095 children aged 6–59 months received Vitamin A supplementation and 12,894 children 6-59 months were treated for severe acute malnutrition (July 2020). COVID-19 accentuated the underlying and immediate causes of child under nutrition, including inadequate diets, sub-optimal health services, poor childcare practices and food insecurity. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:30/07/2020
